<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-407-466  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 407 466.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  April 23 1990 v4 n16 p37(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>House studies costs of on-line computer use. (House ofRepresentatives)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kellner, Mark A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The House Office of Telecommunications Systems is studying ways toreduce the long-distance telephone costs which have increased asrepresentatives take advantage of modem linkage between computersin their home districts and systems located at Capitol Hill.andP;  Bychoosing to use MCI Communications Corp in 1990 instead of the FTS2000 system the House administrators hope to save $1.3 million.andO;Other cost control suggestions include a software change on modemsystems which would cause the systems to hang up after 20 minutesof inactivity.andP;  Some members' offices have evidently failed attimes to turn off their modems, resulting in long-distance callsof three and four days duration.andP;  Another proposal, to limitmembers' long-distance time to 100,000 minutes yearly, has arousedopposition among members who anticipate having to pay forlong-distance usage exceeding the allowance.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   MCI Communications Corp. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    MCIC.andO;Topic:     Government ContractsTelecommunicationsUnited States. Congress. HouseCost ReductionExpenditures.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>